  "category_subtitle": "Learn how to count flat objects in Japanese using 枚",
  "category_detail": "<b>Counting Flat Objects in Japanese</b><br><br>In Japanese, flat and thin objects are commonly counted with the counter <b>「枚」</b>.<br><br>This counter is used for things like <b>paper, tickets, cards, shirts, plates, leaves, photos, stamps, and other flat items</b>.<br><br><b>Basic Pattern</b><br>Most numbers follow the pattern:<br><span class=\"example\">number + 枚</span><br><br>Examples:<br><span class=\"example\">1枚</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(いちまい / ichimai)</span><br><span class=\"example\">2枚</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(にまい / nimai)</span><br><span class=\"example\">3枚</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(さんまい / sanmai)</span><br><br><b>Important Notes</b><br>This counter is easier than some other Japanese counters because its reading pattern is quite regular.<br><br>However, learners should still pay attention to pronunciation and remember that <b>枚</b> is specifically for <b>flat or thin objects</b>, not for general items.<br><br><b>Common Examples</b><br><span class=\"example\">紙を一枚ください。</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(kami o ichimai kudasai)</span><br>Meaning: Please give me one sheet of paper.<br><br><span class=\"example\">切符を二枚買いました。</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(kippu o nimai kaimashita)</span><br>Meaning: I bought two tickets.<br><br>This category focuses on the most useful and natural learner-friendly readings for counting flat objects.",
